		<comments>http://www.notebooks.com/2008/12/12/hp-mini-1000-how-to-upgrade-ram-in-less-than-20-seconds-video/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 12 Dec 2008 08:11:13 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Xavier</dc:creator>
		
		<category><![CDATA[HP Notebooks]]></category>

		<category><![CDATA[netbooks]]></category>

		<category><![CDATA[notebook tips and tutorials]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.notebooks.com/?p=2462</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Today I upgraded my Mini 1000's memory from 1GB to 2GB in less than 20 seconds and I didn't even need to use a screw driver. Upgrading RAM on a notebook is usually a pretty simple task for experienced computer users, but I don't see how HP could've made this any easier on the Mini 1000. Check out this video to see what I mean.


Related posts:<ol><li><a href='http://www.notebooks.com/2008/11/06/hp-mini-1000-video-promo/' rel='bookmark' title='Permanent Link: HP Mini 1000 Video Promo'>HP Mini 1000 Video Promo</a></li><li><a href='http://www.notebooks.com/2008/11/05/hp-mini-1000-mobile-internet-experience-video-demo/' rel='bookmark' title='Permanent Link: HP Mini 1000 Mobile Internet Experience Video Demo'>HP Mini 1000 Mobile Internet Experience Video Demo</a></li><li><a href='http://www.notebooks.com/2008/10/28/hp-mini-1000-netbook-video-demos-specs-and-details/' rel='bookmark' title='Permanent Link: HP Mini 1000 Netbook (video demos, specs and details)'>HP Mini 1000 Netbook (video demos, specs and details)</a></li></ol>]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Today I upgraded my Mini 1000&#8217;s memory from 1GB to 2GB in less than 20 seconds and I didn&#8217;t even need to use a screw driver. Upgrading RAM on a notebook is usually a pretty simple task for experienced computer users, but I don&#8217;t see how HP could&#8217;ve made this any easier on the Mini 1000. Check out this video to see what I mean.</p>
<p>[There is a video that cannot be displayed in this feed. <a href="http://www.notebooks.com/2008/12/12/hp-mini-1000-how-to-upgrade-ram-in-less-than-20-seconds-video/">Visit the blog entry to see the video.]</a></p>
<p>No tools are necessary as there are no screws holdnig the Mini 1000&#8217;s memory door shut. Instead there&#8217;s a little latch next to the one of the battery releases. All you need is a pointy object like a pen or a knife to reach a hole in the latch so you can slide it to the side. The battery door pops off and gives you easy access to the single memory slot.</p>
<p>You can get a 2GB memory stick from NewEgg, Amazon.com or most other online retailers for under $25. HP does not sell the Mini 1000 with 2GB of memory if you order the XP version because of a licensing agreement with Microsoft. When the MIE (Ubuntu) Mini 1000 is released in January you will be able to customize it with 2GB of RAM on HP&#8217;s Web site.</p>


<p>Related posts:<ol><li><a href='http://www.notebooks.com/2008/11/06/hp-mini-1000-video-promo/' rel='bookmark' title='Permanent Link: HP Mini 1000 Video Promo'>HP Mini 1000 Video Promo</a></li><li><a href='http://www.notebooks.com/2008/11/05/hp-mini-1000-mobile-internet-experience-video-demo/' rel='bookmark' title='Permanent Link: HP Mini 1000 Mobile Internet Experience Video Demo'>HP Mini 1000 Mobile Internet Experience Video Demo</a></li><li><a href='http://www.notebooks.com/2008/10/28/hp-mini-1000-netbook-video-demos-specs-and-details/' rel='bookmark' title='Permanent Link: HP Mini 1000 Netbook (video demos, specs and details)'>HP Mini 1000 Netbook (video demos, specs and details)</a></li></ol></p>]]></content:encoded>
